function time_crossing_the_door(arrival, state) {
    const n = arrival.length;
    const answer = new Array(n).fill(0);
    const door_seen_time = [-1, -1];
    let i = 0, t = 0;
    while (i < n) {
        while (t < arrival[i]) {
            t += 1;
        }
        const direction = (door_seen_time[1] !== t - 1) ? 1 : 0;
        if (state[i] === direction) {
            door_seen_time[state[i]] = t;
        } else {
            while (i + 1 < n && arrival[i + 1] === t && state[i + 1] !== direction) {
                i += 1;
            }
            if (i + 1 < n && arrival[i + 1] === t && state[i + 1] === direction) {
                door_seen_time[state[i + 1]] = t;
                i += 1;
            } else {
                t -= 1;
                i -= 1;
            }
        }
        answer[i] = door_seen_time[state[i]];
        i += 1;
        t += 1;
    }
    return answer;
}
```

    The algorithm iterates through the arrival list and checks the last time the door was used (kept in door_seen_time array with separate values for entrance and exit). Based on that information and the given rules, it determines the direction of the door usage at each second (either entrance or exit). Then, it checks if the current person wants to go in the same direction as computed for the current second. If yes, the person is allowed to enter or exit. If not, the algorithm searches for the next person who wants to go in that direction and lets them enter or exit. The algorithm keeps track of the current person index and increases it accordingly. Finally, the time when the current person crosses the door is marked in the answer list. At the end of the algorithm, the answer list is returned.

